    hints: ["Think of the array as a linked list where nums[i] is the 'next' pointer from node i.", "A duplicate value means two nodes point to the same next node — creating a cycle.", "Floyd's cycle detection finds both the meeting point and the cycle entry (duplicate)."],
    clarify: { question: "What would you clarify?", options: ["Can I modify the input array?","Can there be more than one duplicate value?","Must I use O(1) extra space?","Are all numbers guaranteed to be in [1,n]?","Can the duplicate appear more than twice?"], mustAsk: [0,1,2], explanation: "Cannot modify array. Exactly one duplicate value (may appear multiple times). O(1) space required. All values in [1,n] guaranteed." },
    steps: [
      { id: "understand", label: "Problem Understanding", emoji: "🔍", prompt: "Why do the constraints (no modification, O(1) space) rule out the obvious approaches?", why: { question: "Why can't you use a hash set for this problem?", options: ["Hash sets can't detect duplicates","A hash set requires O(n) extra space, violating the O(1) space constraint","Hash sets are too slow"], correct: 1, explanation: "Hash set: O(n) time, O(n) space — simple but forbidden. Sorting: O(n log n) time but modifies array (forbidden). Need an approach that is O(1) space AND doesn't modify input." } },
      { id: "brute", label: "Brute Force", emoji: "🔨", prompt: "How would you find the duplicate with nested loops? What's the complexity?", why: { question: "Why is naive comparison O(n²)?", options: ["For each element, scan the rest for a matching value. n × n comparisons.","Sorting dominates","Two passes needed"], correct: 0, explanation: "Outer loop i: 0..n-1. Inner loop j: i+1..n. Compare nums[i] vs nums[j]. O(n²) comparisons. O(1) space but too slow." } },
      { id: "pattern", label: "Pattern Recognition", emoji: "🧩", prompt: "How does treating the array as a linked list (index→value as next pointer) reveal the duplicate?", why: { question: "Why does a duplicate value create a cycle?", options: ["Duplicates always create issues","Two different indices i and j both have nums[i]=nums[j]=x. Both 'point' to index x. Following pointers: two paths converge at x — that's a cycle entry. x is the duplicate.","Cycles are inherent in arrays"], correct: 1, explanation: "Linked list: node i's next = nums[i]. If nums[i]=nums[j]=x, then both i and j jump to x next. Two entries into node x = cycle entry. Floyd's finds this entry = the duplicate." } },
      { id: "algorithm", label: "Algorithm Design", emoji: "⚙️", prompt: "Walk through Floyd's two phases: cycle detection then cycle entry finding.", why: { question: "In Phase 2, why reset one pointer to index 0 and move both one step?", options: ["Index 0 is always in the cycle","Floyd's theorem: distance(head→cycle_entry) = distance(meeting_point→cycle_entry). Resetting one pointer to head means both reach cycle entry simultaneously.","It works for linked lists only"], correct: 1, explanation: "Mathematical property of Floyd's: after meeting in cycle, head-to-entry distance = meeting-point-to-entry distance (mod cycle length). Both pointers advance 1 step/iteration until they meet at the cycle entry = duplicate." } },
      { id: "tradeoff", label: "Trade-off", emoji: "⚖️", prompt: "Floyd's O(n) O(1) vs binary search O(n log n) O(1) — both valid. When would you choose binary search?", why: { question: "What does binary search on value range look like for this problem?", options: ["Binary search on the array indices","Binary search on values [1,n]: count how many nums[i] ≤ mid. If count > mid, duplicate is in [1,mid]. O(n log n) time O(1) space — simpler logic than Floyd's.","Binary search doesn't apply here"], correct: 1, explanation: "Pigeonhole + binary search: if count of elements ≤ mid exceeds mid, duplicate is ≤ mid. Halve search space. O(n log n) O(1). Simpler than Floyd's but slower. Floyd's is optimal." } },
      { id: "complexity", label: "Complexity", emoji: "📊", prompt: "Time and space complexity of Floyd's approach?", why: { question: "Why O(n) time for Floyd's cycle detection?", options: ["We only scan once","Cycle length ≤ n. Fast pointer catches slow pointer within one full cycle traversal ≤ n steps. Phase 2 also ≤ n steps. Total: O(n).","Amortized over multiple passes"], correct: 1, explanation: "Phase 1: fast pointer laps slow within n steps (cycle ≤ n long). Phase 2: both advance at most n steps to reach entry. Total: O(n) with O(1) space — no auxiliary structures." } },
      { id: "edge", label: "Edge Cases", emoji: "🔐", prompt: "Does Floyd's work when the duplicate appears more than twice? What about duplicates at position 1 or n?", why: { question: "nums=[1,1,1,1,1]: duplicate 1 appears many times. Does Floyd's find it?", options: ["No — only handles exactly 2 copies","Yes — multiple copies means multiple nodes pointing to node 1. Larger cycle but same Floyd's logic applies.","Need special case for n>2 copies"], correct: 1, explanation: "Any number of copies of x: x nodes all point to node x → multiple cycle entries, larger cycle. Floyd's cycle detection is agnostic to number of copies — finds entry regardless." } },
    ],
    dryrun: { question: "nums=[1,3,4,2,2]. Treat as linked list: 0→1→3→2→4→2→4→... (cycle). Phase 1 — slow moves 1 step, fast moves 2. After slow=nums[0]=1, fast=nums[nums[0]]=nums[1]=3: what are slow and fast after 3 total steps each (slow) and 6 total (fast)?", options: ["slow=2, fast=2 (they meet)","slow=4, fast=3","slow=3, fast=4","slow=2, fast=4"], correct: 0, explanation: "Steps: slow: 0→1→3→2. fast: 0→3→2→2→4→2 wait, let's trace: fast=nums[nums[fast]]. Start:slow=0,fast=0. Step1:slow=1,fast=3. Step2:slow=3,fast=2. Step3:slow=2,fast=2. They meet at 2!" },
    pushback: { challenge: "What if you're allowed to modify the array — is there a simpler O(n) O(1) solution?", options: ["Yes: cyclic sort (place each number at its correct index). After sorting, scan for nums[i]!=i+1. But modifies input.","Same Floyd's algorithm","Must use Floyd's regardless"], correct: 0, explanation: "With modification allowed: cyclic sort places nums[i] at index nums[i]-1. First index where nums[i]!=i+1: nums[i] is the duplicate. O(n) time O(1) space. Simpler than Floyd's but destructive." },
    followup: { question: "What if there could be multiple duplicate numbers?", options: ["Floyd's finds only one duplicate entry. For multiple duplicates: XOR won't work. Use binary search approach repeatedly, or hash set if space allowed.","Same Floyd's algorithm finds all","Sort the array"], correct: 0, explanation: "Floyd's cycle entry finds one cycle — one duplicate. Multiple duplicates: binary search variant can find one at a time by narrowing range. Or if space allowed: hash set collects all. Floyd's is specific to single-duplicate case." },
    solution: { approach: "Floyd's Cycle Detection", steps: ["Phase 1: slow=nums[0], fast=nums[nums[0]]; while slow!=fast: slow=nums[slow], fast=nums[nums[fast]]","Phase 2: slow=0; while slow!=fast: slow=nums[slow], fast=nums[fast]","Return slow (cycle entry = duplicate)"], time: "O(n)", space: "O(1)" },
